.ge.com/digital/documentation/cybersecurity","description":"GE's approach to monitoring security mitigations in industrial environments."}]}],"name":"Timely delivery of security patches","description":"A process shall be employed to define a policy that specifies the timeframes for delivering and qualifying security updates to product users and to ensure that this policy is followed. At a minimum, this policy shall consider the following factors: e) The availability of an effective mitigation in lieu of the patch.","details":{"risk_assessment_and_threat_modeling":{"why":"To identify vulnerabilities that require patching and assess the risk of not applying patches in a timely manner.","methodologies":[{"name":"STRIDE","description":"Used to model threats and identify potential security vulnerabilities in the system that may require patching."},{"name":"DREAD","description":"Helps in assessing the risk level of identified vulnerabilities to prioritize patching efforts."}],"tools":[{"name":"NIST 800-30 adapted for SCADA systems","purpose":"Provides a structured approach to risk assessment, tailored for ICS environments."}],"case_study":{"example":"A power plant's DCS was assessed using STRIDE, identifying a critical vulnerability in the control software. A patch was prioritized and delivered within the defined timeframe, mitigating a potential remote code execution risk."}},"audit_and_compliance_verification":{"why":"To ensure compliance with the defined patch delivery policy and verify the effectiveness of mitigations.","audit_checklist":["Verify the existence of a documented patch delivery policy.","Check records of patch deliveries and their timeliness.","Review evidence of mitigations applied in lieu of patches.","Assess the qualification process for security updates."],"metrics":[{"kpi":"Percentage of patches delivered within the defined timeframe","target":"≥95%"},{"kpi":"Number of vulnerabilities with effective mitigations in place","target":"All critical vulnerabilities"}],"compliance_procedure":"Documentation of patch delivery timelines, mitigation strategies, and qualification results must be maintained and reviewed annually."},"training_and_competency_requirements":{"why":"To ensure personnel are capable of managing patch delivery and applying mitigations effectively.","training_programs":[{"name":"ISA/IEC 62443 Cybersecurity Certifications","description":"Provides training on ICS security standards, including patch management."},{"name":"GICSP","description":"Global Industrial Cyber Security Professional certification covers ICS patch management practices."}],"competency_assessment":"Annual reviews of personnel competency in patch management and mitigation strategies, including practical assessments."},"tooling_and_automation_support":{"why":"To streamline the patch delivery process and ensure timely application of patches or mitigations.","tools":[{"name":"Patch Management Systems (e.g., WSUS, SCCM)","purpose":"Automates the distribution and installation of patches across ICS components."},{"name":"Vulnerability Scanners (e.g., Nessus, Qualys)","purpose":"Identifies vulnerabilities that require patching or mitigation."}],"automation_strategy":"Integrate patch management tools with DevSecOps pipelines to automate vulnerability scanning, patch testing, and deployment in ICS environments."},"handling_legacy_systems_and_constraints":{"why":"Legacy systems may not support modern patching mechanisms, requiring alternative mitigations.","strategies":[{"approach":"Network Segmentation","description":"Isolate legacy systems to reduce the attack surface and limit the impact of unpatched vulnerabilities."},{"approach":"Compensating Controls","description":"Implement additional security measures (e.g., firewalls, intrusion detection) to mitigate risks when patches are unavailable."}],"example_policy":"A policy for legacy systems may specify that if a patch cannot be applied within the defined timeframe, the system must be isolated and monitored, with compensating controls documented and reviewed quarterly."},"stakeholder_collaboration_and_governance":{"why":"Effective patch management requires collaboration between security, engineering, and management teams.","governance_model":{"name":"RACI Matrix for Patch Management","roles":[{"role":"Security Team","responsibility":"Identify vulnerabilities and recommend patches or mitigations."},{"role":"Engineering Team","responsibility":"Test and apply patches or implement mitigations."},{"role":"Management","responsibility":"Approve patch deployment timelines and resource allocation."}]},"conflict_resolution":"A documented escalation process for resolving conflicts between security priorities and operational constraints, involving senior management if necessary."},"continuous_improvement_and_updates":{"why":"To adapt the patch delivery policy based on new threats, audit findings, and lessons learned.","update_process":[{"step":"Monitor Threat Intelligence","description":"Regularly review CISA alerts and other sources for new ICS vulnerabilities."},{"step":"Review Audit Findings","description":"Incorporate findings from internal and external audits into the patch management policy."},{"step":"Update Policy","description":"Revise the patch delivery policy annually or as needed based on new threats and lessons learned."}],"lessons_learned":"After a patch-related incident, conduct a root cause analysis and update the patch management policy to prevent recurrence."}},"standard_compliance":"IEC 62443-4-1","last_updated":"2023-10-15"} 
